Introduction

This R Markdown document demonstrates my abilities to use models for data analysis using a data set collected on crickets.

What is that sound?

In this report, we examine what factors predict a crickets chirp rate.

Temperature affects chirp rate

Based on a scatter plot of temperature and chirping, it seems that as temperature increases, the rate of chirping also increases.

Based on a scatter plot of temperature and chirping and a correlation test, it seems that as temperature increases one degree, the rate of chirping increases about 4.2 chirps per minute.

Diamonds Data Analysis

The scatter plot shows that the carat and price has a positive relationship while the boxplot shows that the average price is highest for premium cut.

diamonds <- ggplot2::diamonds

p1 <- ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.2) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "red") +
  labs(title = "Diamond Price vs Carat",
       x = "Carat",
       y = "Price") +
  theme_minimal()

p2 <- ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = cut, y = price, fill = cut)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Diamond Price by Cut Quality",
       x = "Cut",
       y = "Price") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

gridExtra::grid.arrange(p1, p2, nrow = 1)

The correlation plot shows that all variables has strong positive correlation with rspect to price except depth and table.

# Select numeric variables
numeric_vars <- diamonds %>%
  select(price, carat, depth, table, x, y, z)

# Compute correlation matrix
cor_matrix <- cor(numeric_vars)

# Plot heatmap
corrplot::corrplot(cor_matrix, method = "color", type = "upper",
         tl.cex = 0.8, addCoef.col = "black")

The model is fitted with carat, cut, clarity and color as independent variables to predict the price. The model shows that the R square is 91.59%.

# Using carat (continuous) + cut + clarity + color
model <- lm(price ~ carat + cut + clarity + color, 
            data = diamonds)

# View model summary
summary(model)

Checking the assumptions of the model shows that the assumption of linearity and normality are violated.

# Check model diagnostics
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(model)

This is the model with only numeric columns as the predictors. The model shows that except z, all predictors are statistically significant with R square of 85.92% for the model.

model_numeric <- lm(price ~ carat + depth + table + x + y + z, 
                    data = diamonds)

summary(model_numeric)
